ng affects file availability. Generating classes in a separate process could work, but forking a Java process presents challenges.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build strategies**\\n\\nI’m looking at using a system property in build.gradle to set up from the start. This could help exercise debug behaviors in both the JVM and Native environments. I’ll add jvmArgs with the debug location, ensuring that the DebuggingClassWriter sees a non-null value, no matter the initialization order. The user didn't explicitly forbid this; there’s just a limitation on buildArgs. Still, I’m weighing the robustness of combining this with a system property from build.gradle. I'll also need to ensure that necessary classes are available during the native image build.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining initialization issues**\\n\\nI’m considering whether debugLocation might be null if it’s initialized at build time. It seems like it wouldn't initialize unless the tests are tied to the build process. If I’m running tests under both JVM and native conditions, I need to pass runtimeArgs for native. However, if the initialization happens at build time, I might need buildArgs as well. There could be a way to avoid modifying the build by using System.setProperty in the test itself.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_CtOyWCt57Zda3Thq4QMt3SCZ|fc_0915a4173ec1635b0169f5abff6b088190a08443997baceb56", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.springframework/spring-core/5.3.15/user-code-filter.json"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1177, "output": 1759, "cacheRead": 19968, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 22904, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777708008821, "responseId": "resp_0915a4173ec1635b0169f5abe9445881909c7d489361e97567"}}
